Here‚Äôs the thing, I think Americans - at least in-part - are skeptical of the surveillance state not for reasons that have to do with any principles of privacy, but, instead, for reasons rooted in our skepticism that were a UAE like system to be hacked‚ÄîWe wouldn‚Äôt be made whole, would be left in a lurch, and would end up fucked.

I.e., we don‚Äôt trust our government to actually foot any bills that they aren‚Äôt being forced to pick up through protracted and complex litigation.

It‚Äôs easy to trust a surveillance state when you live in a country whose entire ethos is built on the principle of protecting ‚Äúlocals.‚Äù

Here we eat our own and we regulate fuck-ups through - for the most part - capitalist driven large scale/complex litigation; the problem with this is that it only incentivizes for regulatory infractions that can turn a profit to be enforced strictly while allowing for fracking waste to make drinking water flammable with zero repercussions.

Obviously this is an apple to oranges comparison, but at the heart of both examples is that our government has never proven itself to be reliable or responsible when attempting to correct its own fuck-up‚Äôs and errors.

So surveillance here kinda works in a dynamic where even though there is no harm being internalized by the surveillance itself‚ÄîThe possibility of harm arising from the surveillance due to actions that are more incompetent and less nefarious is too high to stomach for some.

And I think that‚Äôs a fair position. I don‚Äôt know that I agree, but to take the UAE example‚ÄîIf my identity would have been stolen the last time my passport was lost by the passport office I have m zero percent faith that the office would have done a single goddamn thing to help me deal with the messy, stolen-identity, aftermath.

Imo, the distrust is not rooted in notions of privacy - as the guest mentioned early in the episode Americans aren‚Äôt generally that principled when faced with a moral question that weighs inconvenience against a non-internalized liberty interest - and instead the issue with surveillance is that we - for good reason - are distrustful of the government‚Äôs willingness to hold itself accountable for any harm or breaches that could arise in the future. (Which is low probability, but the potential level of harm is so high - e.g., someone gets your social - that it still presents a strong case against supporting any calls to further our surveillance state.

Unlike the government, corporations can be sued, so we know that if Apple were to fuck up that we‚Äôd be made whole because the lawsuits would be immediate and aggressive, which serves as an incentive for Apple to have a number of safeguards in place.

In order for Americans to have more faith in the government‚ÄîWe would need for Congress to work towards making the government more readily subject-able to civil suits for massive money damages because if we continue to provide broad/varied forms of immunity from litigation, then the government has zero incentive to protect our information because any harm that could come from having a shit system would be entirely externalized costs.

Western Europe may depend directly on Russian oil, but they also depend economically on mineral reserves throughout Africa and the Middle East, and Russia and China do also. I'm a psychologist who conducts assessments of future behavior, mainly selection and risk assessments in occupations where identifying risks is critically important. So I engage in prediciton, and one of the things I do is sniff out frauds. I remain suspicious of Mr. Bustamante. He has an excess of confidence in his predictions not typically seen in those with the deepest level of expertise.  Predicting the future is very hard. Each for their own reasons, ideologues, know-nothings, and con artists often have an air of persuasive certainty about the future. Ideologues see what they want to see. Con artists want you to see what they want you to see, and they know that an air of hyper-confidence fools a lot of people. Know-nothings don't know how much they don't know,  so their confidence in their thoughts isn't tempered by meta-cognition (thinking about their own thinking). Genuine experts tend to hedge more than others when making predictions. They talk more readily about risks, probabilities, ifs, uncertainties, and multiple scenarios.  So Bustamante's confidence set off alarms in me. He presents as way too confident for an expert. We'll see, I guess. Winter isn't here yet a lot can happen. I am definitely no expert in global geopolitics, and certainly not an expert in the Russia-Ukraine war, but I'd have expected a much more nuanced and less certain analysis from someone who truly knows what he's talking about.

Going back and listening to his Ukraine analysis is interesting. Some of it is already leaning towards being wrong. And this is what I hate about listening to "experts" on any one subject because I have learned the bigger the organization the less anyone person will know how things work (at least at the granular level). Gov't agencies already operate in basically siloed information hubs within office/departments let alone across the entire agency. Regular gov't agencies work on a need to know basis in any non-classified setting because as a gov't worker you are not productive if you are listening to a briefing that has nothing to do with your job or department (for that matter most private sector jobs work like that). I won't pretend to know how classified settings work in gov't, but I am very familiar with non-classified setting in govt, so cia, fbi, nsa and all the other intelligence agencies are going to silo information even more then regular federal agencies. But, who knows maybe classified information is shared more then non-classified information LOL not being sarcastic at all üòâ. Which, to bring it back to my point is that any single cia, fbi employee, etc is not going to have a comprehensive understanding of every topic discussed and they might not even have a comprehensive understanding of what their own field is because of how large a topic it might be, for example most departments have a whole team dedicated to doing analysis on that topic let alone multiple agents doing the same job. Now, I'm not saying that any single gov't employee in the CIA or FBI can't have a operational understanding of how things are done or as we like to say, a 50,000 feet understanding of how things are done. But, the take away is that even people that understand how things are done rely on their employees reports and other departments reports to make their own reports and assessments and every single one of them will still ask questions even if they have been doing the job for 30+ years, so that's why listening to a single employee that arguably was not that high up in the CIA is not a great temperature gauge of how things are done and take their assessment with a grain of salt as they are probably making wild assumptions about all the parts they were not involved in. And in my experience even people that have worked in any agency for 30+ years still don't know basic questions to things that they sometimes work on. I mean, think about it the amount of information is always going to be too much to remember over any long period of time especially 30 yrs. In poker we identify this perspective as "levelling" a "level 1 thinker" thinks what do I have, and how should I play it. A "level 2 thinker" is thinking. This is what I have, how do I play WHILE also thinking what could my opponents have, the game being trying to figure the answer to that question based off answers. A "level 3 thinker" is thinking "I think my opponents capacity is above level 1, and probably at level 2, so what this level 2 thinker think I have, and based off that, how should I play based off these assumptions. Level 4 would be "what does my opponent think that I think their hand is, and it just goes from there. Most people in poker, and in life, are just thinking level 1. imho
